06167nam a22008415i 9783110767995DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107679957 a10.1515/97831107679952doi  a(DE-B1597)602130  a(OCoLC)1419789556  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aHQ73.3.J3 7aSOC0060002bisacsh00aBeyond Diversity :bQueer Politics, Activism, and Representation in Contemporary Japan /ced. by Kazuyoshi Kawasaka, Stefan Würrer. 1aDüsseldorf : bdüsseldorf university press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (XI, 190 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on translation and transliteration -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: A new age of visibility? LGBTQ+ issues in contemporary Japan -- tThe progress of LGBT rights in Japan in the 2010s -- tSame-sex partnerships in Japan: Would legalization mean deradicalization? -- tLGBTQ human rights in Japanese laws and policies -- tBeing LGBT in disasters: Lived experiences from Japan -- tQueer politics and solidarity: Post-Cold War homonationalism in East Asia -- tMedals and conspiracies: Chinese and Japanese online trans-exclusionary discourses during the 2020 Tokyo Olympic Games -- tTranscending the gendered body? Transphobia and the construction of the self in the writing of Shōno Yoriko -- tFeeling the friction: Reworking Japanese film studies/criticism from a queer lens -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aJapan presents a unique context for conducting queer studies. Unlike Europe, North America, and other regions of the world, it is said to lack homophobia due to the absence of Christianity as moral foundation. Furthermore, the situation of LGBTQ+ people has changed rapidly over the past ten years, as the Tokyo Olympics provided another impulse for discussions about sexual minority rights. As a result, recent surveys show a dramatic increase in the acceptance of same-sex marriage. However, Japan is the only G7 country that does not recognize same-sex partnerships and sexual minorities are not legally protected from discrimination. This is due to deeply rooted traditional and religiously tainted family values, represented and perpetuated by post-war Japan's deeply conservative political establishment. While LGBTQ+ issues in Japan have received scholarly attention since the 1990s, there is little scholarship in English on developments after 2000, let alone in the form of anthologies. This volume will bridge this gap by shedding light on political and cultural representations of and by sexual minorities in Japan after 2000, making, thus, available in English a completely novel perspective on LGBTQ+ issues in Japan and East Asia.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSex rolezJapan. 0aSexual minoritieszJapan. 4aGeschlechterrolle. 4aJapan. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aLGBT. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aJapan.  aLGBTQ+.  agender identiy.1 aFukunaga, Genya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamano, Saori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawasaka, Kazuyoshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawasaka, Kazuyoshi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKhor, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKubo, Yutaka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLifu, Guo, econtributor.4ctb4h